bug.short_desc: Entering invalid schema import location in XMLExamples hangs Eclipse

long_desc.thetext: This happens specifically when using the Catalogue.xsd file. Here are the steps to reproduce: 1. Create a new Editing and validating XML files example. 2. Open Catalogue.xsd under the PublicationCatalogue folder. 3. In the design view, add a new import. 4. Right click on the import and select Show properties. 5. In the properties view, enter a Schema location of asdf.xsd. 6. In the Prefix test field enter asdf. 7. Click back in the Schema location text field. Eclipse hangs.
We're not handling invalid schema locations well. Although it is a bad problem, I don't believe it is a stop ship for 151. Will target the fix for 152.
I'm OK with deferring to 1.5.2. This doesn't seem to be a problem with every schema.
Yes, you don't see the problem if the XML Schema namespace has a prefix in the namespace entries table,
Created an attachment (id=51381) Patch to org.eclipse.wst.xsd.ui

We should not update the model when there file location of the import is invalid.
The fix:
Simple check to see if the file location is valid. If it is invalid, then processing returns.

Problem: Under some circumstances, when a user adds an import, we inadvertantly corrupt the schema which causes the model to enter into an infinite loop which causes the workbench to hang.
Cause: When you add an invalid schema location for an import, and then change the prefix for it, we try to update the namespace table map and inadvertantly remove the entry for the schema namespace.
Solution: Add a check to see if the schema location is valid, and if it is not, just return.
Risk Assessment: Low. See the patch. Use the boolean isValidSchemaLocation. I've tested this thoroughly.
change from if (oldPrefixValue.equals(newPrefix)) return; to: if (oldPrefixValue.equals(newPrefix) || !isValidSchemaLocation) return;
Bug 160710 has been opened to track this problem from an XML Schema model point of view to see if there's more we can do to bullet proof the model so that it doesn't go into a loop under these circumstances.
If this is approved, I will also bump up the service version number of the plugin. (This change is not included in the patch).

bug.short_desc: getPredefinedDataTypeFormattedName doesn't handle all types

long_desc.thetext:
I am having trouble generating the DDL for a Table that contains a column whose PredefinedDataType's PrimitiveType is PrimitiveType.TIME where the PredefinedDataType supports precision. Basically, I want to generate a column whose type is "TIME(3)".
The problem comes down to the getPredefinedDataTypeFormattedName method in org.eclipse.datatools.connectivity.sqm.internal.core.definition.DatabaseDefinitionImpl. That method does not take into account cases where a PrivitiveType.TIME supports precision. It simply returns predefinedDataType.getName() as the type's formatted name. It seems to me that it should check if the type supports precision and, if it does, include the precision in parentheses (just as is done for TIMESTAMP).
As far as I can tell, I am unable to extend the DatabaseDefinitionImpl class to work around this problem. The DatabaseDefinitionRegistryImpl creates instances of the DatabaseDefinitionImpl for each of the plug-ins that extend the databaseDefinition extension point. That class doesn't seem to give me the opportunity to provide a class that implements the DatabaseDefinition interface that provides for my special needs.
A second problem along this line is that I will be wanting to generate columns whose type is "TIME(n) WITH TIME ZONE". (Also "TIMESTAMP(n) WITH TIME ZONE".) It seems to me that this would be accomplished if the TIME and TIMESTAMP cases in the getPredefinedDataTypeFormattedName method would check to see if the type supports a display name and, if so, inserts the precision into the display name using the MessageFormat.format method in the way as is done for the BINARY and INTERVAL types.
Are these problems that should be addressed in the DatabaseDefinitionImpl class or is there some way that I can provide a class that extends DatabaseDefinitionImpl (or otherwise implements DatabaseDefinition) so that I can provide my own support for these types?

bug.short_desc: [model] The CompilationUnit associated with an IJavaElementDelta does not include diagnostics generated from APT

long_desc.thetext: The javadoc on IJavaElementDelta.getCompilationUnitAST says that it returns "the compilation unit AST created by the last reconcile operation", which seems to imply that it has been processed by both the main jdt compiler and any annotation processors. But when I call getProblems() on that AST I only get diagnostics from the base compiler (syntax errors, bad types, etc) and not any that were generated by an annotation processor, even though those do show up in the source view.

APT uses ReconcileContext#putProblems(...) to report problems. This specifies that these problems are reported to the problem requestor, not added to the AST. Also CompilationUnit#getProblems() specifies that the problems are the one created by the compiler (not by a compiler participant). Works as designed.

bug.short_desc: [1.5] [compiler] Eclipse compiler wildcard bug

long_desc.thetext:
Eclipse compiles the following code with no errors reported: class A<T extends Number, S extends T> { A<? extends Long,? extends S> a; } This code shouldn't compile. Capture conversion of A<? extends Long, ? extends S> is A<X,Y> where X has upper bound Long & Number, and Y has upper bound S & X. Now, X and Y should be subtypes of the bounds defined in A. X is subtype of Number, but Y is not subtype of X. Even in the first place S & X is not formed correctly since S and X are not in subtype relation. To make things more clear we can see possible actual values for all type variables or wildcards. T = Number, S = Number, ? extends Long = Long, ? extends S = Integer. But Integer is not subtype of Long, so the A<? extends Long,? extends S> is not valid.
It seems that capture conversion is not implemented correctly.
javac 1.5.0_08 and 6.0b99 also accept this code.

(In reply to comment #1) > javac 1.5.0_08 and 6.0b99 also accept this code. >
Yes, I checked that and I believe it's a bug there as well.

For original issue, the spec is usually considering that some constructs are tolerated at compile-time, since there is no way to construct the offending type. Certain cast checks are based on this assumption. Will investigate still.

You might be right that the type should be allowed. Wildcards should be viewed as imposing additional constraints on type parameters. And reading the JLS capture conversion and intersection type specs, it seems that the type is ok. Having said that, the offending assignment from my last example should then definitely be allowed.
After discussing this with people that know type systems (i.e. my advisor) I can see that this is not a bug. It is really hard to get this from JLS alone I guess. My mistake, sorry for trouble.
Added regression test in org.eclipse.jdt.core.tests.compiler.regression.GenericTypeTest#test1043/1044/1045

(In reply to comment #8) > Added regression test in > org.eclipse.jdt.core.tests.compiler.regression.GenericTypeTest#test1043/1044/1045 >
test1044 should be rechecked. I believe that's a bug actually. javac does allow that declaration. A<? extends Object> in that case would be capture converted to A<X> where X is a new type variable with bound Object & Number, which is a proper intersection type. Object & Number is subtype of Number, so original bounds are also satisfied. I don't see the reason why A<? extends Object> would be disallowed.

When tuning compiler for bug 202404, I realized your claim on the capture was valid. Reopening.
Re: comment 9 > A<? extends Object> in that case would be capture converted to A<X> where X is > a new type variable with bound Object & Number, which is a proper intersection > type. Object & Number is subtype of Number, so original bounds are also > satisfied. I don't see the reason why A<? extends Object> would be disallowed.
I think the capture in this case shouldn't yield Object&Number, but simply Number, but this doesn't change the fact your last example should be accepted.

bug.short_desc: New bugs that are assigned to not send e-mail to component inbox

long_desc.thetext: If someone creates a new bugzilla and assigns it to himself, people watching that component's inbox are not notified about that bug. The result is that a bug can be opened, changes made, released, and the bug closed, without other committers/interested parties of that component knowing.

There is one Bugzilla issue that would solve that problem. But it looks like that this won't make it into the next Bugzilla release.
https://bugzilla.mozilla.org/show_bug.cgi?id=76794 (Implement the ability to watch components)
But there is another one that could work as a workaround. https://bugzilla.mozilla.org/show_bug.cgi?id=38922 (Default (Initial) CC list for each component)
Another workaround could be to make the "Assign To" field read only/disabled on the "Enter Bug" page (even for committers). This way there would be at least one mail notifying the inbox watcher about the new bug and a second mail about the assignment change.

Yes, this is in Mozilla's hands. An RSS feed of a search result could be of some help here.
Closing as WONTFIX here because there's not much I can do about it. Feel free to add comments to the Bugzilla bugs listed in comment 1.

bug.short_desc: Add hook for obfuscation

long_desc.thetext:
For building commercial products based on eclipse a hook for obfuscation in an automated build is needed. This includes also the build of update-sites. At the moment there is only a possibility to enable/disable signing of jars but ONLY for "packaged" builds - not for update-site-builds
What would be usefull is a hook which is called every time a jar was generated.

Please check the page http://help.eclipse.org/help32/topic/org.eclipse.pde.doc.user/guide/tasks/pde_custom_callbacks.htm
These hooks have been added to address this kind of problems. Closing for now, but please let us know if this is still a problem.

We are aware of these hooks.
The problem is, that most obfsucators work on jars and not on class files.
Note that the build.jars target does not build any jar files in the PDE context (!) Instead of that, the jar files are created by several zip targets in different places e.g. build.update.jars and in the main task of the packager's ant file.
There is neither a common place where the jar files for plugins are created nor is there a hook to be called directly after the creation of a jar file, no matter if you are building a packaged product or an update site.

Hooks have been added in HEAD, see org.eclipse.pde.build/templates/headless-build/customAssembly.xml.
This file must be copied into the builder directory.
There are pre.jarsigning and post.jarUp targets which may be used to obfuscate.

bug.short_desc: [rename method] renames wrong method

long_desc.thetext: Move to JDT/UI
It sounds to be a Search Engine issue as searching for declaration of Zhope.method() in project returns ZhopeBase.method-) as exact match!

Finally, problem is in JDT/UI land as it search for declaration ignoring declaring and return types... Perform a search using Java Search dialog correctly returns only one match... => move back to JDT/UI

This is a feature, not a bug ;-)
The Rename Method refactoring renames all related methods in the ripple (up and down the type hierarchies). If we would not do this, the refactoring would produce compile errors.
See also explanation in bug 83293.

Although I agree that current solution for #83293 makes sense, this case is a bit different, because a) method in ZhopeBase has a bit different signature and b) there are not two interfaces but base class AND interface. I can even imagine situation when such a splitup (i.e. partil renaming of the methods) may be what is really necessary. Perhaps it worth to add a warning + checkbox and let user decide if to rename all implementations/declarations or just part of them. In case of large hierarchy selecting each class manually might be very inconvenient and error prone.

> a) method in ZhopeBase has a bit different signature
No, the signatures are the same (no parameters). Modifiers don't matter here (and are actually also equal because interface methods are implicitly public).
> b) [..] I can even imagine situation when such a splitup (i.e. partil > renaming of the methods) may be what is really necessary.
I agree that this is sometimes necessary, but unfortunately, it can't be done with an automated refactoring. If you have a variable 'ZhopeChild ch' and a call 'ch.method()', then there's no way to tell which method was "really" meant.
Agree. But I did mean just warn user about the conflict and let him decide which branch (or both) to rename. Silent operation here is not a best choice.

bug.short_desc: Support paragraph indent in StyledText

long_desc.thetext:
The following methods (as of 3.2) are used to indent the first line of a paragraph.
StyledText#setIndent(int) StyledText#setLineIndent(int, int, int)
However, using word wrap, it is desirable that subsequent lines also use the same indent as the first line, effectively "a left margin" to the paragraph. This behavior would be consistent with bulleted lists in many other text-based editors and viewers.
FH is there a way to do this currently?

something like left margin would do?
*** This bug has been marked as a duplicate of 56342 ***

I think the intent of this report is different than bug 56342, though it's possible that they could have a common solution. The other bug is referring to the (lack of) margin around the outside of StyledText that allows its text to practically reach the visual bound between the StyledText and its container composite. OTOH, Texts have a couple of pixels of margin around the outside.
I think left margin, assuming it could be set on a per-line basis, would be perfect.

I agree with Grant, the description of bug 56342 is not precise enough to be a duplicate of this report. If the solution to that bug report is a single margin for the entire StyledText widget, not a separate margin per-line, then this bug is different.

I think having so many APIs to "allocate white space in front of a line" would be very confusing for the user.
setIndent() setMarin (int,int,int,int) Bug 56342 setOutDent()/setWrapIndent() Bug 115432 (this isn't what you want?)

I think these three bugs require only a single addition to the interface -- assuming I understand them correctly. Bug 5632 lacks important technical details (e.g., is it solved by the widget layout margins or does it required per-line margins?) and bug 115432 has a very specific goal -- what I need is somewhere in between. The problem centers upon a need to move towards a per-line model of indentation, distinguishing the current "setLineIndent" method as a first-line indentation solution, only, whether or not word-wrap is enabled.
In general, there are two types of indent I am familiar with that appear to be covered by all three bug reports: first line indent (which is what setLineIndent does) and the hanging indent (for subsequent wrapped lines). The setIndent(int indent) method affects the entire widget, which I've personally never had to do. Here's an approach to solve this:
Add another method, setIndent(int indent, int line), in which the text at the given line number "line" is left justified by the number of characters "indent". Let the setLineIndent(int startLine, int count, int indent) behavior modify the indentation of the first line, only, which is what it does. However, the setLineIndent operation must now account for the setIndent(int indent, int line) left margin, which establishes a baseline indentation for the line honored by the word-wrap behavior.
For example, here are some possible configurations to ground this approach:
int indent1, indent2, line;
setIndent(indent1, line) setLineIndent(line, 1, indent2).
If indent1 > 0 and indent2 > 0, we get a normal paragraph left justified at (indent1) characters from the left of the widget and the first line at (indent1 + indent2) characters from the left of the widget. All wrapped lines are appear at (indent1) characters from the left of the widget.
If indent1 > 0 and indent2 < 0, we get a paragraph with the first line at (indent1 - indent2) from the left of the widget and all subsequent wrapped lines at (indent1) from the left of the widge. I believe this is the outdent behavior.
By default, setIndent(indent, line) = 0 for all "line" from 0 to getLineCount().
What do you think?

Sorry, the proposal in my last comment violates the current expected behavior of setLineIndent()... an alternative approach, that respects backwards compatibility, is to use a method setWrapIndent(int line, int indent) that only affects the indentation for wrapped lines that result from the given line number -- this indentation is independent of the behavior of setLineIndent() that affects the first line, only.
This is the same problem as bug 115432.
*** This bug has been marked as a duplicate of 115432 ***

Here is a patch for this problem.
The error shows up because validation is turned on in headless parsing mode. The J2EE folks suggested that we disable validation by adding the following line:
RendererFactory.getDefaultRendererFactory().setValidating(false);
This patch disables validation inside AntDefaultingOperation, it later restores the original value in the (new) AntRestoringCommand.

Severity lowered to major since reasonable workarounds exist. Deferred to 1.5.3 since the fix, though simple in spirit, is more than the proverbial one-liner.
Also, a question about AntRestoringCommand, specifically about whether we really need it, and the consequences in error scenarios if we do.
1. Do we need to restore the default RendererFactory's validation state at the end of the task when run from the command line given the JRE process terminates at the end of the task?
2. When the task is run from within the Eclipse IDE, will the RendererFactory's validation state ever be true? My understanding is this bug only happens from the command line, not from the Eclipse IDE in which the UI head is active. If we don't need to monkey with the RendererFactory's validation state when running from the IDE, then we don't need to restore anything.
3. If for some reason we really do need to restore RendererFactory's validation state from false back to true at the end of our task, could RendererFactory be left in an unhealthy state if our task excepted before AntRestoringCommand got a chance to execute()?

Hi Chris, to summarize what we talked about:
I think you are correct that in the command-line env, we don't need to restore the validation state because the JRE will terminate. However, in the IDE, the RendererFactory's validation state actually does come up as true (although the EAR association problem is not manifested in the IDE); this is why the AntRestoringCommand was added.
For your third concern, you suggested that we can use the undo mechanism to restore the validation status if the ant task hits an exception. I talked to Peter about this, we would need to make some small changes to the ant command framework to ensure the undo is run, as outlined below:
- In CommandFragmentEngine (~line 404), the dataManager_.process( cmd ); statement should be moved inside the try block to guard against exceptions happening in the getters/setters.
- In AntController (~line 77), we need to check for an error status and initiate the undo sequence.
